<li id="cite_note-19"><b><a href="#cite_ref-19" title="">^</a></b> Mitton, Jacquelin. "<i>The Penguin Dictionary of Astronomy</i>", Penguin (1993) p.148</li>
<li id="cite_note-20"><b><a href="#cite_ref-20" title="">^</a></b> This is calculated for a fixed latitude by knowing the star's <a href="/wiki/Declination" title="Declination">declination</a> (δ) using the formulae (90°+ δ). Alpha Centauri's declination is -60° 50′, so the latitude where the star is circumpolar will be south of -29° 10′S or 29°. Similarly, the place where Alpha Centauri never rises for northern observers is north of the latitude (90°+ δ) N or +29°N.</li>
